Google DeepMind published "From AGI to ASI," a 60-page research paper laying out four distinct trajectories by which AI systems could move from human-level intelligence to superintelligence. Path one is continuous scaling — more compute, more data, bigger models, the trajectory behind Gemini and its successors. Path two is algorithmic discontinuity — fundamentally new architectures that don't resemble today's transformers, producing capability jumps that scaling alone can't explain. Path three is recursive self-improvement — models that begin iterating on their own architectures and training processes, compressing years of human research into automated loops. Path four is collective intelligence — many AGI-level agents coordinating into emergent systems whose combined capability exceeds any individual component. DeepMind's framing is notable for its intellectual honesty: the paper treats all four paths as live possibilities rather than betting exclusively on scaling, which has been the dominant assumption in the field.
